 Install and Use a Generic Cloud Environment as a Private Cloud (Using AWS)
We'll use AWS EC2 + VPC to simulate a private cloud environment. This is the simplest approach — no extra software needed beyond your AWS account.

✅ What You'll Need

An AWS account (free tier works)
A browser
Basic knowledge of what a cloud is


STEP 1: Sign In to AWS

Go to https://aws.amazon.com
Click Sign In to the Console
Log in with your credentials


STEP 2: Create a VPC (Your Private Cloud Network)
A VPC (Virtual Private Cloud) is essentially your own private section of AWS — this is your private cloud.

In the search bar at the top, type VPC and click it
Click Create VPC
Fill in:

Name tag: my-private-cloud
IPv4 CIDR block: 10.0.0.0/16
Leave everything else as default


Click Create VPC

✅ You now have a private cloud network.

STEP 3: Create a Subnet Inside Your VPC

On the left menu, click Subnets
Click Create Subnet
Fill in:

VPC: Select my-private-cloud
Subnet name: my-subnet
Availability Zone: Pick any (e.g., ap-south-1a)
IPv4 CIDR block: 10.0.1.0/24


Click Create Subnet


STEP 4: Launch an EC2 Instance (Your Virtual Machine in the Private Cloud)

Search for EC2 in the top bar and click it
Click Launch Instance
Fill in the details:

FieldValueNamemy-private-cloud-vmOS ImageUbuntu Server 22.04 LTS (Free tier)Instance typet2.micro (Free tier)Key pairClick Create new key pair → name it my-key → Download itNetworkSelect your VPC: my-private-cloudSubnetmy-subnetAuto-assign public IPEnable

Click Launch Instance


STEP 5: Connect to Your Instance (Access Your Private Cloud)

Wait 1–2 minutes for the instance to start
Go to EC2 → Instances, select your instance
Click Connect (top right)
Choose the EC2 Instance Connect tab
Click Connect

✅ A terminal window opens in your browser — you are now inside your private cloud VM!

STEP 6: Set Up the Cloud Environment (Install OpenStack-lite / Basic Cloud Tools)
Run these commands one by one in the terminal:
bash# Update the system
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

# Install basic cloud management tools
sudo apt install -y apache2 curl wget git

# Start the web server (simulates a cloud service)
sudo systemctl start apache2
sudo systemctl enable apache2

# Check it's running
sudo systemctl status apache2

STEP 7: Verify the Output (See Your Cloud Service Running)

Go back to your EC2 instance page
Copy the Public IPv4 address (shown in the instance details)
Open a new browser tab and paste the IP:

   http://<your-public-ip>

You should see the Apache2 Ubuntu Default Page

✅ This confirms your private cloud environment is running a web service!
